HEADWORD: Troy
<hw>Troy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Troy weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Troy weight</b></col>, <cd>the weight which gold and
silver, jewels, and the like, are weighed. It was so named from
<etsep>Troyes</etsep>, in France, where it was first adopted in Europe.
The troy ounce is supposed to have been brought from Cairo during the
crusades. In this weight the pound is divided into 12 ounces, the ounce
into 20 pennyweights, and the pennyweight into 24 grains; hence, the
troy ounce contains 480 grains, and the troy pound contains 5760 grains.
The avoirdupois pound contains 7000 troy grains; so that 175 pounds troy
equal 144 pounds avoirdupois, or 1 pound troy = 0.82286 of a pound
avoirdupois, and 1 ounce troy = 1⟦frac17x175⟧ or 1.09714 ounce
avoirdupois. Troy weight when divided, the pound into 12 ounces, the
ounce into 8 drams, the dram into 3 scruples, and the scruple into 20
grains, is called <xex>apothecaries' weight</xex>, used in weighing
medicines, etc. In the standard weights of the United States, the troy
ounce is divided decimally down to the ⟦frac1x10000⟧ part.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troyounce</ent>⟦br⟧
